{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516226"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12581"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12581"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.14,0.03,0.68,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34266"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5077"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19440"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/34266"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents for her routine follow-up. She had complains of joint pain and swelling for which she is under treatment. Her medical history includes systemic lupus erythematosus. On examination her blood pressure is 142/98 mmHg, pulse 86/min and temperature 37.1\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. She has a rash on her cheeks and there is diffuse tenderness and swelling of her finger joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERoutine investigation shows a white cell count of 8.6 x 10*9/L (4 - 11) with a lymphocyte count of 0.9 x 10*9/L ,1.0 - 3.5). Routine urinalysis shows proteinuria, microscopic haematuria, red blood cells and red blood cell casts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations will be most appropriate in assisting in diagnosis and management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound KUB","Renal function test","Intravenous pyelogram","Renal biopsy","24-hour urine protein"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe above given urinalysis in a patient with SLE are suggestive of lupus nephritis, a common complication of SLE. Lupus\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Enephritis is an inflammation of the kidneys, a type of glomerulonephritis caused by systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease. \u003Cstrong\u003ERenal biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eis the investigation of choice for the diagnosis and grading of lupus nephritis. It helps to determine the extent and severity of kidney damage as well as assists in treatment decisions, such as the use of immunosuppressive therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound KUB\u003C/strong\u003E may help detect abnormalities in the urinary tract, such as hydronephrosis, kidney stones, cysts etc. but it has no specific role in lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are a series of blood tests that assess the function of the kidneys, including tests for creatinine, blood urea nitrogen (BUN), and glomerular filtration rate (GFR). While it can help to assess the severity of kidney damage and monitor the progression of kidney disease, it is not specific for lupus nephritis. In this case, a renal biopsy would be a more definitive test to confirm the diagnosis of lupus nephritis and guide treatment decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous pyelogram\u003C/strong\u003E is an imaging test that involves injecting a contrast dye into the veins and taking X-rays to visualise the urinary tract. While it can help to detect structural abnormalities in the kidneys and urinary tract, such as obstruction or tumours, it also has no significant role in lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine protein\u003C/strong\u003E is a test that quantifies the amount of protein excreted in the urine over a 24-hour period. It helps in assessing the severity of proteinuria and monitor the progression of nephrotic and nephritic syndrome but not of lupus nephritis while the biopsy helps in grading and planning treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Renal biopsy is the gold standard investigation for lupus nephritis."],"references":["Musa R, Brent LH, Qurie A. Lupus Nephritis. [Updated 2022 Aug 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19440"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12581"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/19440"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-04-02T08:46:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T23:07:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5077"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"34266"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji"